title.narrative: COMMUNITY RESILIENCE

description.narrative: Households and communities are resilient to climate change and economic shocks, and are supported to overcome chronic vulnerabilities that affect children, which contributes to Child Health, Disaster Risk Reduction, Environmental Sustainability, Equitable Access To Quality Education, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children (Covid), Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Sanitation, Social Protection, Social Protection (Covid), Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition, Water. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Girls and boys grow up in resilient, inclusive and child friendly communities, that are supported by enabling environment and systems that provide an equitable chance in life.

title.narrative: Households and communities are resilient to climate change and economic shocks, and are supported to overcome chronic vulnerabilities that affect children

description.narrative: Humanitarian cash transfers, delivered through existing government systems with technical support of UNICEF, benefited 7,899 households with lean season support and 31,587 households with early recovery support after Cyclone Idai induced flooding. The latter were complemented by safe water supply and integrated awareness messages helped to strengthen community copying capacity reaching more than 511,772 flood affected people during humanitarian situations. Overall, during 2019 UNICEF delivered critical immediate life-saving and life-sustaining assistance to people affected by cholera, food insecurity and floods reaching a total of over 600,000 people (including 329,030 children), as well as recovery interventions for affected people. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:16/12/2019
